			<translation>
				Let him do whatever can be done by a private man, but it will not be enough in place of many daring deeds. <!-- CG: Unclear. -->
				Let him never be entirely corrupted by the charms or trifles of the world. Let him never stop or grow cold. 
				Let him be tempted, excited, and increased only by something of value. And as long as he can, let him do this
				expertly, subtly, profoundly; but he will be wanting in any opposition from people, or the weight of things, <!-- CG: Unclear! -->
				or the bulk of actions. This is quite necessary, and with such divine art in dealing with people, things, actions 
				in a most suitable, prudente, strong, and solid manner.
				Nor is any industriousness ever diligent enough, or magnanimity tranquil enough.
				When he ceases joking, he will wither.
			</translation>
